          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>üá∏üá© European-made weapons found in Sudan</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           A France 24 <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-04-2025-h4-1-investigation-is-ongoing?source=weebsite" target="_blank">investigation is ongoing</a> EU weapons in Sudan, despite an EU arms embargo. The French outlet traced Bulgarian-made mortar shells, produced by EU-based company Dunarit, to Sudan‚Äôs battlefield. Videos filmed by Sudanese fighters in November 2024 showed 81mm explosive mortars and documents linking the ammunition to Bulgaria.. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Abu Dhabi-based defense contractor International Golden Group bought the mortars. They were sent through eastern Libya, where Khalifa Haftar, an ally of the UAE, maintains control. Bulgaria denied directly exporting to Sudan. They stated that the transaction was permitted to a government without sanctions. However, experts say this transfer still breaks EU embargo rules. This raises concerns about arms being diverted through intermediaries and raises questions about the UAE‚Äôs involvement in the Sudanese civil war. </p>
        </mj-text>
