      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>üáÆüá≥India proposes low-cost financing for arms to lure in Russia's traditional customers</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">India is <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-18-04-2025-h5-1-ramping-up-its-defense-export?source=weebsite" target="_blank">ramping up its defense export</a> strategy by offering long-term, low-cost financing via its Export-Import Bank to nations that traditionally relied on Russian arms. Key markets include Brazil, Algeria, Morocco, Argentina, Ethiopia, and Cambodia - nations whose military systems are often compatible with Indian equipment.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">India aims to double its defense exports to $6B by 2029. Indian arms are significantly cheaper, with shells priced at $300 to $400 compared to around $3,000 for European equivalents. This push comes as Russia‚Äôs war in Ukraine disrupts global arms flows. However, India faces scrutiny after a Ukrainian report identified an Indian-made component in Russian equipment, raising concerns about end-use monitoring and export controls in conflict zones.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
